# TrainIQ AI / AI Coach — Cursor Rules

## Component Generation Rules (Data-Driven UI)

Use this section whenever generating or refactoring UI for workout analysis, anatomy, or biomechanical dashboards. The UI must be **data-driven**: never invent exercise-specific layouts; bind to the API/analysis payload shape.

---

Act as an Elite Sports-Tech Frontend Architect and Kinesiology UI Expert.
Your task is to build a dynamic, hyper-accurate UI component for "TrainIQ AI", an application that analyzes workout videos and provides real-time biomechanical feedback.

### CRITICAL REQUIREMENT: DATA-DRIVEN ACCURACY

The UI must be perfectly structured to handle dynamic sports-science data for any exercise. Do not hardcode specific exercises. The UI must adapt accurately to the following JSON-like data structure that will be passed to it:

#### 1. Anatomical Breakdown Module

Create a UI section that clearly separates muscles into categories:

- **Primary Muscles** (e.g., Deltoids) — Highlight these visually (e.g., brighter neon text or icons).
- **Secondary/Assisting Muscles** (e.g., Pectoralis Major) — Muted visual weight.
- **Stabilizers** (e.g., Core) — Clearly indicated.

**UI Rule:** Use collapsible accordions or clean list cards for anatomy so it doesn't clutter the screen, especially for complex exercises.

#### 2. Form Analysis & Scoring Module (The Core Feature)

Create a dual-list component: **"מה לתקן"** (Needs Fix) and **"מה היה טוב"** (Good Form).

**Dynamic Status Indicators:**

- If a metric is a warning/error (e.g., "Camera angle too low", "Pose engine unavailable"), use an **Alert UI** (subtle amber/orange or red glowing border, not intrusive, but noticeable). Include icons like `!` or Warning.
- If a metric is positive (e.g., "Good eccentric control"), use a **Success UI** (Neon Green `#22c55e` glow or checkmark ✓).

Ensure each feedback point can display a **percentage impact** (e.g., `-5%`, `+5%`) elegantly aligned to the logical edge of the card (use RTL-aware alignment: `text-start`/`ms-auto` patterns in Tailwind, or logical properties in plain CSS).

#### 3. Coach's Corner & Actionable Cues

Design a premium **"Pro Tip"** card section specifically for coach feedback.

It must support **structured text**: A main cue (e.g., "Core Stability") and a mental visualization (e.g., "Stomach Punch"). Use typography to distinguish the title from the explanation.

#### 4. Metrics Bar (TUT, RPE, Stability)

Create a horizontal or grid-based metrics dashboard at the bottom or top of the analysis.

It must **handle missing data gracefully**. If "TUT" (Time Under Tension) is `null` or `"לא זמין"`, display it with a muted gray placeholder rather than breaking the UI.

#### 5. Design & RTL Rules

- Maintain the ultra-premium `#0b0c10` dark theme with `#22c55e` / `#34d399` accents and glassmorphism.
- **Strict RTL** (Hebrew) layout.
- Ensure the component is **highly modular**. Build it as a set of smaller components (`AnatomyList`, `FeedbackCard`, `MetricBadge`, etc.) that are assembled in the main `AnalysisView`.

---

## Reference: canonical analysis view props (illustrative)

Maps to existing server/client fields where applicable; extend only with typesafe guards.

```ts
// Illustrative — align names with actual API JSON from server.js / index.html render paths
interface AnalysisViewModel {
  exercise: { key: string; nameHe: string; nameEn?: string };
  muscles: {
    primary: Array<{ nameHe: string; nameEn?: string }>;
    secondary: Array<{ nameHe: string; nameEn?: string }>;
    stabilizers: Array<{ nameHe: string; nameEn?: string }>;
  };
  fixes: Array<{
    title: string;
    body?: string;
    severity?: 'error' | 'warning' | 'info';
    impactPct?: number | null; // negative = penalty
  }>;
  positives: Array<{
    title: string;
    body?: string;
    impactPct?: number | null;
  }>;
  coach: {
    headline?: string;
    cueTitle?: string;
    cueBody?: string;
    mentalImage?: string; // e.g. "Stomach Punch"
  };
  metrics: {
    tutSec?: number | null;
    rpe?: number | null;
    stability?: number | null; // 0–100 or null
    symmetry?: number | null;
    labels?: Partial<Record<string, string>>; // Hebrew display labels
  };
  warnings?: Array<{ code?: string; messageHe: string; severity: 'warning' | 'error' }>;
}
```

When implementing in the current codebase (`index.html` single-page app), prefer **pure functions** that map API JSON → view model, then **DOM builders** or small template literals per sub-component to avoid duplication.
